# Build artifacts and local environment
node_modules/
web/.next/
web/out/
contracts/out/
contracts/cache/
contracts/broadcast/
relayer/bin/
relayer/internal/chain/bindings/
.env
.env.*
artifacts/demo/*

# ...except a public chain's published paperwork, which has to travel with the repo.
#
# The consignment is the shop's own published record — the tranche roots, each item's leaf, and the
# pointer its voucher's bytes live at. `web/scripts/sync-artifacts.mjs` turns it into the static file
# the browser fetches, and it runs at BUILD time. Vercel builds from a git checkout and nothing else,
# so a consignment that is not committed is a consignment Vercel cannot see: the sync says "no
# consignment yet", the build succeeds, and the deployed shop has an empty shelf and not one tag that
# can be verified. Local chains stay ignored — theirs is regenerated by a script in seconds.
#
# Re-including has to walk down a level at a time: git will not resurrect a file whose parent
# directory is excluded, so the directory is un-ignored first and only then the file.
!artifacts/demo/16602/
artifacts/demo/16602/*
!artifacts/demo/16602/consignment.json
artifacts/deployments/31337.json

# Projections of the contracts and of a deployment, generated by web/scripts/sync-artifacts.mjs.
# A hand-touched projection is a lie waiting to happen, so none of these are tracked.
web/lib/chain/generated/*

# ...except the ABIs, for the same reason the consignment travels: a hosting build cannot make them.
#
# They are a projection of `contracts/out`, which is Foundry's output — gitignored and absent from a
# git checkout. Vercel has no Foundry, so it can only use what was committed. Regenerate locally
# (where the contracts are actually compiled) and commit the result; the sync script skips the
# regeneration when there is no `contracts/out` to regenerate from.
!web/lib/chain/generated/abi.ts
web/public/deployments
web/public/blobs
web/public/consignment.json
